Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is. The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Questions for Analysis¶

  1. How does number of movies compare per release year?
  2. Change in revenue generated by movies over the years?
  3. In which months were the most/least movies released?
  4. Which genre has the highest number of movies?
  5. Which director has produced the most movies?
  6. How does budget and popularity put in for a particular movie or genre relate with revenue generated? i. Popularity vs revenue ii. Vote Aerage vs Revenue iii. Budget vs Revenue
  7. Genre distribution over the years by popularity?
  8. Movie runtime analysis: What is the average runtime? How does runtime compare with popularity?
  9. What is the correlation between popularity and profit?
  10. Movies with the ighest and lowest revenue and their directors?
  11. What movies had the highest and least runtime?
  12. Characetristics of movies with highest revenues i.e., what were the budgets, who are the actors, under what genres do they fall?

#creating a function, data, which will split the string and return the count of each genre.
def data(x):
    #concatenate all the rows of the genres.
    data_plot = df[x].str.cat(sep = '|')
    data = pd.Series(data_plot.split('|'))
    #conts each of the genre and return.
    info = data.value_counts(ascending=False)
    return info
total_genre_movies = data('genres')

#Separating Data contained in Cast & Genres into Multiple values Source
# Columns like cast & genres contain several values contained in a single cell separated by the "|" ,
# so we need to separate these values to make a more appropriate analysis.
def seprate_values(col):
    new_cols=(df[col].str.split('|', expand=True).rename(columns=lambda x: f"{col}_{x+1}"))
    return new_cols
df_gen = seprate_values('genres')
df_cast = seprate_values('cast')
df['cast'],df['genres']=df_cast['cast_1'],df_gen['genres_1']
display(df['cast'].value_counts().nlargest(10))
print('-'*60)
display(df['genres'].value_counts().nlargest(10))

import pprint
#defining the function
def calculate(column):
    #for highest value
    high= df1[column].idxmax()
    high_details=pd.DataFrame(df1.loc[high])
    
    #for lowest value
    low= df1[column].idxmin()
    low_details=pd.DataFrame(df1.loc[low])
    
    #collecting data in one place
    info=pd.concat([high_details, low_details], axis=1)
    
    return info

#function which will take any column as argument from and keep its track 
def data(column):
    #will take a column, and separate the string by '|'
    data = profit_data[column].str.cat(sep = '|')
    
    #giving pandas series and storing the values separately
    data = pd.Series(data.split('|'))
    
    #arranging in descending order
    count = data.value_counts(ascending = False)
    
    return count
#variable to store the retured value
count = data('genres')
#printing top 5 values
count.head()

#ploting the graph

From the above visualization, we see that the most profitable movies lie under genres: Comedy, Action, Drama, Adventure in that order, with Western being least.

Conclusions¶

  • There is increase in number of movies produced each year, as the years move by.
  • From a general perspective, revenue generated by movies has increased over the years, only dropping slightly in the late 2000s to the 2010s.
  • September is leading in number of movies released, followed by October, December then January.
  • Drama has the highest number of movies followed by comedy; action, thriller and adventure come closely after.
  • There is a relatively strong correlation between budget and revenue: 0.63
  • Per our analysis, it was noted that over the years, there has been notable growth in popularity for most of the genres. Standing out were Drama, Comedy and Action.
  • The average runtime of most movies is 102 minutes.
  • At 0.63, we can conclude that there is a relatively stron correlation between popularity and profits for a movie. More watched movies realize more returns.
  • From our analysis, the most profitable movies lie under genres: Comedy, Action, Drama, Adventure in that order, with Western being least.
  • Tom Cruise, Tom Hanks, Sylvester Stallone, Denzel Wwashigton and Jim Carrey rank top five in the top performing movie categories.
  • Average budget for this category of movies(with profits > $50M was 60444957.76083707.
